# Dense Low-Rank Pair Policy + Pair-MCTS Architecture Spec

## 0. Purpose

This spec defines a new model/search path:

```text
model_family = global_pair_lowrank_0
search_mode  = sampled_joint_pair_lowrank_v1
```

It preserves the V1 pair-action search contract, but replaces the expensive “proposal pass + admitted-pair graph scoring pass” with a **dense low-rank pair policy surface**:

[
L(i,j)
======

M_i + M_j
+
\operatorname{PairDot}(i,j)
+
\operatorname{PairFeatureBias}(i,j)
]

where (i,j) are start-of-turn legal cells.

The model does **not** materialize all pair tokens as graph inputs. Instead, it emits per-legal-cell embeddings and scalar marginal logits. Pair scores are computed on demand, or blockwise, from those per-cell outputs.

The key design principle:

> The low-rank matrix gives a dense **pair-prior parameterization**. It does not magically give a dense **MCTS training target**. Search targets remain candidate-conditional unless the legal pair set is exhaustively searched.

The existing V1 architecture already requires unordered pair actions, full Rust legal rows, candidate metadata, tactical support as proposals/labels rather than hard solvers, and candidate-aware replay targets. This spec keeps those contracts intact. 

---

# 1. Non-negotiable runtime contracts

## 1.1 Pair action semantics

The runtime action after the opening is:

```text
PairAction = unordered canonical pair of two distinct start-of-turn legal cells
```

For a normal two-placement turn:

```text
PairAction {i, j}
```

must satisfy:

```text
i != j
i is in the full Rust start-of-turn legal row table
j is in the full Rust start-of-turn legal row table
{i, j} has exactly one canonical pair key
```

The pair key must be independent of order:

```text
pair_key(i, j) == pair_key(j, i)
```

The first placement inside the turn must not expand, shrink, reorder, or otherwise change the legal table from which the second placement is drawn. This is required for unordered pair-action MCTS to match the game abstraction.

Hexo’s actual game rule is that after the opening, every turn consists of two placements by the same player; the game is played on an infinite hex grid with a placement radius, and the win condition is six in a row. The two-placement rule is what makes both 5-windows and 4-windows immediate win-in-one-turn threats. 

## 1.2 Rust authority

Rust owns:

```text
legal row construction
legal row hash / schema identity
tactical payload construction
game state transition
pair application
terminal detection
MCTS tree traversal
PUCT / Gumbel / widening
backup
final action selection
```

Python owns:

```text
graph construction from Rust-provided state data
model inference
low-rank pair score computation
candidate reservoir construction
source metadata construction
training target construction
```

Python never chooses the final move directly. It only supplies candidate rows, logits, value estimates, and metadata. This follows the current V1 implementation boundary where Rust owns legal-row identity, tree traversal, PUCT, progressive widening, backup, and final action choice, while Python supplies inference and candidate reservoirs. 

## 1.3 Tactical support is not a solver

Exact tactical facts are required candidate-support facts and training labels. They are not allowed to censor the legal table or force normal two-placement actions.

On normal two-placement turns:

```text
legal_row_mode = full_rust_legal
tactical_mode  = proposal_and_label
search_required = true
```

Hardcoded non-search actions are allowed only for true structural exceptions:

```text
opening_single
engine_declared_single_placement_terminal_exception
terminal
```

A normal post-opening 5-window or 4-window state must still go through pair search, though tactical completion pairs must be protected from candidate eviction.

## 1.4 Unsampled pairs are not negatives

The search target is never allowed to assume:

```text
legal pair not admitted => bad pair
```

Training must distinguish:

```text
searched candidate
explicit searched weak candidate
explicit sampled negative with valid metadata
tactical-protected candidate
diagnostic canary
unadmitted legal pair
```

The low-rank model can score every pair, but unless search or an oracle produced target support over every pair, the loss must remain candidate-conditional.

