# 5. Heads

## 5.1 Value head

The value head returns a scalar from the **current player’s perspective** at the node being evaluated.

```text
value_logit = MLP_value(G_state)
value = tanh(value_logit)
```

Shape:

```text
value: float[]
```

Range:

```text
[-1, 1]
```

Rust converts the value to the relevant root or node perspective during backup.

No silent zero fallback is allowed. Missing value is an inference error, matching the current V1 implementation’s requirement that `value` is mandatory. 

## 5.2 Cell marginal head

For each legal cell:

[
M_i = f_M([H_i, G])
]

Implementation:

```text
cell_input_i = concat(H_legal[i], G_state, H_legal[i] * W_gated(G_state))
cell_marginal_logits[i] = linear(MLP_cell(cell_input_i))
```

Shape:

```text
cell_marginal_logits: float[N]
```

Uses:

```text
candidate source: cell_marginal_cross
auxiliary training target
component of pair logit
diagnostics
```

This head is not allowed to choose the final move.

## 5.3 Low-rank pair embedding head

The simplest user-proposed version is:

[
L(i,j) = M_i + M_j + e_i^\top e_j
]

Recommended default is a slightly more expressive unordered two-tower version:

[
\operatorname{Dot}(i,j)
=======================

\frac{1}{2\sqrt{d_r}}
\left(
Q_i^\top K_j + Q_j^\top K_i
\right)
]

where:

```text
Q = W_Q H_legal
K = W_K H_legal
Q, K: float[N, d_pair_rank]
```

Default rank:

```text
d_pair_rank = 64
```

Recommended ablations:

```text
32
64
128
```

The symmetrized two-tower version can represent “cell i wants a partner of type k” better than a single shared embedding while preserving unordered pair symmetry.

If the simpler shared-dot variant is used:

[
\operatorname{Dot}(i,j)
=======================

\frac{E_i^\top E_j}{\sqrt{d_r}}
]

then set:

```text
Q = K = E
```

## 5.4 Cheap pair feature bias

The dense pair prior may include cheap pair features:

[
B(i,j) = w_\phi^\top \phi_{\text{cheap}}(i,j)
]

Required cheap features:

```text
axial_distance_bucket
same_axis
same_line
same_window_any
same_window_count_bucket
both_touch_same_hot_window
both_touch_opponent_hot_window
one_is_own_winning_single
one_is_opponent_cover_cell
legal_phase_flags
```

These must be computable either:

```text
on demand for one pair
or blockwise for candidate retrieval
```

Avoid expensive tactical or oracle-derived high-order features in the dense prior unless they are already available in the Rust tactical payload.

## 5.5 Dense low-rank pair logit

Default formula:

[
L_0(i,j)
========

\alpha_M(M_i + M_j)
+
\alpha_D
\frac{Q_i^\top K_j + Q_j^\top K_i}{2\sqrt{d_r}}
+
w_\phi^\top \phi_{\text{cheap}}(i,j)
+
b
]

Recommended parameterization:

```text
alpha_M = softplus(raw_alpha_M)
alpha_D = softplus(raw_alpha_D)
```

Initialization:

```text
raw_alpha_M: initialize near 1.0 effective scale
raw_alpha_D: initialize near 0.1 effective scale
w_phi: zero or small normal
b: 0
Q/K projections: Xavier or small normal
```

Reason: early training should not let random pair embeddings dominate candidate retrieval.

For unordered pairs:

```text
L_0(i, j) == L_0(j, i)
```

Diagonal entries are invalid:

```text
L_0(i, i) = -inf
```

## 5.6 Optional admitted-candidate residual

The dense low-rank pair prior should be the main scorer. However, pure dot-product interaction may underfit relational pair tactics. Therefore the model may include a candidate-only residual:

[
R(i,j)
======

\operatorname{MLP}*{\text{pair}}
(
G,
H_i + H_j,
|H_i - H_j|,
H_i \odot H_j,
\phi*{\text{full}}(i,j)
)
]

Final pair logit for admitted candidates:

[
L_{\text{final}}(i,j)
=====================

L_0(i,j)
+
\lambda_R R(i,j)
]

Recommended:

```text
lambda_R = learned scalar
initialize lambda_R = 0.0 or 0.1
```

Candidate-only full pair features:

```text
axial distance
same-axis
same-line
same-window
terminal exact win flag
terminal-equivalent win flag
terminal exact cover flag
covers-all-opponent-win-requirements flag
impossible-to-cover state flag
legal-row phase flags
```

Do not feed source labels by default:

```text
source_type
source_rank
was_tactical_protected
was_direct_retrieval
```

Those are useful for metadata and ablations, but feeding them into the main scorer risks shortcut learning.

## 5.7 Pair completion auxiliary head

Recommended optional head:

[
C(i,j)
======

M_j
+
\frac{A_i^\top B_j}{\sqrt{d_c}}
]

where (i) is an anchor and (j) is a completion candidate.

Shapes:

```text
A: float[N, d_completion]
B: float[N, d_completion]
pair_completion_logits(i, j): computed on demand or blockwise
```

This supports an autoregressive-style auxiliary target:

```text
p(second = j | first = i)
p(second = i | first = j)
```

Both orientations must be trained when meaningful. Training only the canonical first cell is forbidden.

## 5.8 Tactical auxiliary head

The model should predict tactical labels as auxiliary supervision:

```text
terminal_tactical_v1
```

Recommended outputs:

```text
own_winning_single_logit[N]
opponent_cover_cell_logit[N]
own_hot_completion_pair_logit over admitted/tactical pair rows
opponent_cover_pair_logit over admitted/tactical pair rows
impossible_to_cover_logit scalar
```

Rust tactical payload remains the source of truth. The model’s tactical head does not define legality and does not force moves.

