# 19. What this architecture improves over the current V1 path

This spec gives the pair-MCTS path a true global pair-prior surface:

```text
any legal pair can be scored from per-cell outputs
```

without introducing all-pair graph tokens.

Compared with the current implementation description, the main practical improvement is:

```text
current: proposal graph pass -> candidate rows -> final pair-row graph pass
new:     one graph encoder pass -> low-rank pair surface -> candidate reservoir
```

The current implementation’s two-pass model path is coherent, but it risks becoming wall-clock expensive because each expanded node may require both proposal inference and final admitted-pair scoring. The low-rank spec makes final pair scoring a cheap operation over cached legal-cell outputs. 

The main statistical improvement is that pair supervision generalizes across pairs. A target on pair `{i,j}` updates:

```text
M_i
M_j
Q_i / K_i
Q_j / K_j
```

which affects other structurally similar pairs. That is better than treating every admitted pair row as an isolated sparse object.

The main caveat remains:

```text
dense model logits != dense search target
```

So this should be implemented as:

```text
dense low-rank pair prior
+
bounded candidate-aware MCTS
+
candidate-conditional targets
```

not as:

```text
full legal-pair AlphaZero target over unsearched actions
```

That distinction is the difference between a trainable architecture and a self-reinforcing candidate-generator imitation loop.
